featureDescription.name: isLastSegment
featureDescription.description: CAS de-multipliers need to know whether a CAS is the last multiplied segment. Thus CAS multipliers should set this field to true for the last CAS they produce.

typeDescription.name: de.tudarmstadt.ukp.dkpro.core.api.metadata.type.ProcessorMetaData
typeDescription.description: Information about a CAS processor such as a reader, analysis engine, multiplier, or consumer.

featureDescription.name: instanceId
featureDescription.description: Unique identifier for this processor instance. If the same processor is applied multiple times to the CAS in different configurations, each application has a unique instance ID. In a clustered environment, each cluster node running a processor in a particular configuration should produce the same instanceId.

featureDescription.name: name
featureDescription.description: Name of the processor as per the 'name' field in the processor meta data.

featureDescription.name: version
featureDescription.description: Version of the processor as per the 'version' field in the processor meta data.

featureDescription.name: annotatorImplementationName
featureDescription.description: Java class implementing the processor.

typeDescription.name: eu.excitement.type.entailment.Decision
typeDescription.description: String subtype that describe entailment Decision. *Note*: If you extend/change this type, you *MUST* also update "enum TEDecision" in the entailment core.

typeDescription.name: eu.excitement.type.entailment.Text
typeDescription.description: This type represents a text part of a T-H pair. This type annotates a text item within the TextView. It can occur multiple times (for multi-text problems).

typeDescription.name: eu.excitement.type.entailment.Hypothesis
typeDescription.description: This type represents a hypothesis part of a T-H pair. This type annotates a hypoth- esis item within the HypothesisView. It can occur multiple times (for multi-hypothesis problems)

typeDescription.name: eu.excitement.type.entailment.Pair
typeDescription.description: This type represents a text-hypothesis pair.

featureDescription.name: pairID
featureDescription.description: ID of this pair. The main purpose of this value is to distinguish a certain pair among multiple pairs.

featureDescription.name: text
featureDescription.description: This feature points a Text instance, which rep- resents the text part of this pair.

featureDescription.name: hypothesis
featureDescription.description: This feature points a Hypothesis instance, which represents the hypothesis part of this pair.

featureDescription.name: goldAnswer
featureDescription.description: This features records the gold standard answer for this pair. If the pair (and CAS) represents a training data, this value will be filled in with the gold standard answer. If it is a null value, the pair represents a entailment problem that is yet to be answered.

typeDescription.name: eu.excitement.type.entailment.EntailmentMetadata
typeDescription.description: This type provides metadata for entailment problem.

featureDescription.name: task
featureDescription.description: This string holds the task description which can be found in the RTE challenge data.

featureDescription.name: channel
featureDescription.description: his feature can holds a string that shows the channel where this problem was originated. For example, "customer e-mail", "online forum", or " customer transcription", etc.

featureDescription.name: origin
featureDescription.description: This metadata field can hold a string that shows the origin of this text and hypothesis. A company name, or a product name.

featureDescription.name: TextDocumentID
featureDescription.description: This field can hold a string that identifies the doc- ument of the TextView. This feature must have a value, if TextCollectionID is not null.

featureDescription.name: TextCollectionID
featureDescription.description: This field can hold a string that identifies the collection name where the document of the TextView belongs to.

featureDescription.name: HypothesisDocumentID
featureDescription.description: This field can hold a string that identifies the document of the HypothesisView. This feature must have a value, if HypothesisCollec- tionID is not null.

featureDescription.name: HypothesisCollectionID
featureDescription.description: This field can hold a string that identi- fies the collection name where the document of the HypothesisView belongs to.

featureDescription.name: language
featureDescription.description: Language of this CAS.

typeDescription.name: eu.excitement.type.predicatetruth.PredicateTruthValue
typeDescription.description: This type provides labels for PredicateTruth. This type is a string subtype that only permits "PT+", "PT-", and "PT?".

typeDescription.name: eu.excitement.type.predicatetruth.PredicateTruth
typeDescription.description: This type represents a predicate truth value annotation.

featureDescription.name: value
featureDescription.description: This represents the value of the annotation.

typeDescription.name: eu.excitement.type.predicatetruth.ClauseTruthValue
typeDescription.description: This type provides labels for ClauseTruth. This type is a string subtype that only permits "CT+", "CT-", and "CT?".

typeDescription.name: eu.excitement.type.predicatetruth.ClauseTruth
typeDescription.description: This type represents a clause truth value annotation.

featureDescription.name: value
featureDescription.description: This represents the value of the annotation.

typeDescription.name: eu.excitement.type.predicatetruth.NegationAndUncertainty
typeDescription.description: This type represents a negation-and-uncertainty annotation.

featureDescription.name: value
featureDescription.description: This represents the value of the annotation.

typeDescription.name: eu.excitement.type.predicatetruth.NegationAndUncertaintyValue
typeDescription.description: This type provides labels for NegationAndUncerntainty. This type is a string subtype that only permits "NU+", "NU-", and "NU?".

typeDescription.name: eu.excitement.type.predicatetruth.PredicateSignature
typeDescription.description: This type represents an implication signature of a predicate.

typeDescription.name: eu.excitement.type.predicatetruth.PredicateSignatureValue
typeDescription.description: This type provides labels for PredicateSignature. This type is a string subtype that only permits one of the following strings: "+ / -", "+ / ?", "? / -", "- \ +", "- / ?", "? / +", "+ / +", "- / -", "? / ?".

typeDescription.name: eu.excitement.type.semanticrole.Predicate
typeDescription.description: Predicate is a uima.tcas.Annotation. It represents a predicate. It holds the predicate sense as string and links to its arguments (An array of Argument). It has the following features: - predicateName (uima.cas.String): This feature represents the name of this predicate. It actually refers to the sense of the predicate in PropBank or FrameNet. -arguments (uima.cas.FSArray):This feature is an array of EXCITEMENT.semanticrole.Argument. It holds the predicate's arguments.

featureDescription.name: predicateName
featureDescription.description: This feature represents the name of this predicate. It actually refers to the sense of the predicate in PropBank or FrameNet.

featureDescription.name: arguments
featureDescription.description: This feature is an array of semanticrole.Argument. It holds the predicate's arguments.

typeDescription.name: eu.excitement.type.semanticrole.Argument
typeDescription.description: It represents an argument (of semantic role labeling). It has two features; the argument's semantic role (type), and a backward reference to the predicate that governs the argument.

featureDescription.name: argumentName
featureDescription.description: This feature represents the semantic role (type) of this argument. The fact that this feature is a String means that arbitrary role labels can be adopted, such as the PropBank argument set (A0, A1, AM-LOC, etc.), the FrameNet role set (Communication.Communicator, Communication.Message, etc.), or any other.

featureDescription.name: predicates
featureDescription.description: This feature is an array of semanticrole.Predicate. (Backward) references to the predicates which governs it.

typeDescription.name: eu.excitement.type.temporal.DefaultTimeOfText
typeDescription.description: It is anchored to a textual region (a paragraph, or a document), and holds the "default time" that has been determined for this passage and can be useful to interpret relative time expressions ("now", "yesterday") in the text.

featureDescription.name: time
featureDescription.description: This feature holds the default time for the textual unit which is annotated by this annotation. The time string is expressed in the normalized ISO 8601 format. More specifically, it is a concatenation of the ISO 8601 calendar date and extended time: "YYYY-MM-DD hh:mm:ss".

typeDescription.name: eu.excitement.type.temporal.TemporalExpression
typeDescription.description: TemporalExpression annotates a temporal expression. It is a uima.tcas.Annotation that annotates a temporal expression within a passage, adding a normalized time representation. It holds two string features: One contains the original temporal expression, and the other contains a normalized time representation, using ISO 8601. This is the top annotation for temporal expressions, with a normalized time representation. It has four subtypes, which reflects TIMEX3 temporal types of Date, Time, Duration and Set

featureDescription.name: text
featureDescription.description: his feature holds the original expression appearing in the text.

featureDescription.name: resolvedTime
featureDescription.description: This feature holds the resolved time in ISO 8601 format. For example, "Yesterday", will be resolved into "2012-11-01", etc. See the type DefaultTimeOfText for details.

typeDescription.name: eu.excitement.type.temporal.Date
typeDescription.description: This type represents a temporal expression of type Date. The expression describes a calendar time like yesterday, November 1943, Tuesday 18th, etc.

typeDescription.name: eu.excitement.type.temporal.Time
typeDescription.description: This type represents a temporal expression of type Time. The expression refers to a time of the day, even if in a very indefinite way: eleven in the morning, late last night, twenty after twelve, etc.

typeDescription.name: eu.excitement.type.temporal.Duration
typeDescription.description: This type represents a temporal expression of type Duration. The expression describes a duration with explicit durations: 2 months, 48 hours, all last night, 20 days, etc.

typeDescription.name: eu.excitement.type.temporal.Set
typeDescription.description: This type represents a temporal expression of type Set. For example, every winter, each Monday, etc. It indicates a recurrence pattern.

typeDescription.name: eu.excitement.type.alignment.Target
typeDescription.description: This is a CAS annotation type that can point one or more annotations (tokens, parse nodes, NER nodes, or any annotations) It is a list that groups annotations in one View. The target type allows flexible alignment between any data, including structures made by multiple annotations. Note on usage: begin holds the minimum begin value among annotations in targetAnnotations. Likewise, end should point the maximum end among annotations.

featureDescription.name: targetAnnotations
featureDescription.description: This is a FSArray that can hold one or more annotations. A target should mark one or more annotations

typeDescription.name: eu.excitement.type.alignment.Link
typeDescription.description:
- CAS type that links two Target. - Multi-view type: a Link connects one target in T (TextView), the other target in H (HypothesisView).
The semantic of a "Link" is: The texts (or structures) pointed by "TSideTarget" and "HSideTarget" have a relation of "type", with the direction of "direction", on a strength of "strength".
We make no assumptions regarding what annotations are aligned by Link and Target types. One Target can be linked by an arbitrary number of Link, also a Target can group an arbitrary number of Annotations. Note that uima.tcas.Annotation is the super type of almost all CAS annotation data. Since a Target can group Annotation, it can group any type of annotations in CAS.
Some notes on Link type usage. (Indexing and setting begin - end) - A Link instance should be indexed on the Hypothesis View. So one iteration over the Hypothesis view can get all alignment links. - begin and end : both span value should hold the same value to that of HSide Target

featureDescription.name: TSideTarget
featureDescription.description: This feature points one Target in TEXTVIEW side. A mandatory value, and should not be null. The semantic of a "Link" is: The text (or structure) targets have the relation of "type" between them, with the direction of "direction".

featureDescription.name: HSideTarget
featureDescription.description: This feature points one Target in HYPOTHESISVIEW side. A mandatory value, and should not be null. The semantic of a "Link" is: The text (or structure) targets have the relation of "type" between them, with the direction of "direction".

featureDescription.name: strength
featureDescription.description: This feature keeps one double (numerical) value. Mandatory value, and should not be null. The value indicates the strength of the relation.

featureDescription.name: directionString
featureDescription.description: This value denotes the "direction" of the alignment.Link. Enum-like value that holds one of "TtoH", "HtoT", or "Symmetric".

featureDescription.name: alignerID
featureDescription.description:
This is the first part of 3 ID strings for the alignment.Link instance. The string denotes the idetification of the aligner (or underlying resource).
It is the convention to use getID() method of alignment.Link to get the concatenated, unique string for the instance. getID() returns such a string by concatenating 3 ID strings: alignerID + alignerVersion + linkInfo

featureDescription.name: alignerVersion
featureDescription.description:
This is the second part of 3 ID strings for the alignment.Link instance. The string denotes the sub-identification of the aligner (or underlying resource) --- which are generally the version (or date).
It is the convention to use getID() method of alignment.Link to get the concatenated, unique string for the instance. getID() returns such a string by concatenating 3 ID strings: alignerID + alignerVersion + linkInfo

featureDescription.name: linkInfo
featureDescription.description:
This is the thrid part of 3 ID strings for the alignment.Link instance. The string denotes the internal information about the added link; for example "synonym" (in WordNet based aligner), "stronger-than" (in VerbOcean based lexical aligner), or "local-entailment" (some aligner that aligned multiple structures). Thus, the value is defined by the aligner, and enable alginer to denote more than one relations that is identifiable by getID().
It is the convention to use getID() method of alignment.Link to get the concatenated, unique string for the instance. getID() returns such a string by concatenating 3 ID strings: alignerID + alignerVersion + linkInfo

featureDescription.name: groupLabel
featureDescription.description:

typeDescription.name: eu.excitement.type.alignment.Direction
typeDescription.description:
A string sub-type for direciton marking. This type is a enum-like value that holds all possible directional marker for alignment.Link. This value is only to be used within an alignment.Link instance.
Allowed values are: "TtoH", "HtoT", "Symmetric"

value.description: The relation is from TSideTarget to HSideTarget.
The relation is from HSideTarget to TSideTarget
The relation is a bidirectional (symmetric) one. (Both TSideTarget to HSideTarget and HSideTarget to TSideTarget.)
